# Combinational Logic (Verilog)

## Overview
This directory contains Verilog implementations of basic combinational logic circuits.

Combinational circuits produce outputs that depend only on the current inputs, without any memory or clock dependency.

---

## 🧠 Concepts Covered

- Arithmetic circuits
- Data selection and routing
- Encoding and decoding
- Comparison operations

---

## 📁 Modules Included

- **Adder**  
  Performs binary addition of two inputs.

- **Subtractor**  
  Performs subtraction between two inputs.

- **Multiplexer (MUX)**  
  Selects one input from multiple inputs based on control signals.

- **Demultiplexer (DEMUX)**  
  Routes a single input to one of many outputs.

- **Encoder**  
  Converts multiple input lines into a binary-coded output.

- **Decoder**  
  Converts binary input into one-hot output signals.

- **Comparator**  
  Compares two inputs and determines their relation (equal, greater, or less).

---

## ⚙️ Tools Used

- Verilog HDL  
- Xilinx Vivado  

---

## 🎯 Learning Focus

- Writing combinational logic using `assign` and `always` blocks  
- Understanding propagation of signals without clock dependency  
- Designing modular and reusable components  

---

## 🧪 Notes

- All designs are written to be synthesizable  
- Testbenches may be added separately using SystemVerilog  

---

## 📌 Summary

This section builds the foundation for more complex digital systems by focusing on stateless logic design.
